**Question:**

```java
void sendAlert(int[] alerts) {
  for (int i = 0; i < alerts.length; i++) {
    if (alerts[i] == 1) {
      System.out.println("Alert 1");
    }
    if (alerts[i] == 2) {
      System.out.println("Alert 2");
    }
    if (alerts[i] == 3) {
      System.out.println("Alert 3");
    }
  }
}
```

**Answer:**

```java
void sendAlert(int[] alerts) {
  Map<Integer, String> alertMessages = new HashMap<>();
  alertMessages.put(1, "Alert 1");
  alertMessages.put(2, "Alert 2");
  alertMessages.put(3, "Alert 3");

  for (int alert : alerts) {
    if (alertMessages.containsKey(alert)) {
      System.out.println(alertMessages.get(alert));
    }
  }
}
```

**Explanation:** This example showcases a Long Method code smell due to the repetitive if conditions checking for each alert type separately. The refactored version utilizes a `HashMap` to store alert codes and their corresponding messages, which reduces redundancy and simplifies the logic. This approach not only makes the code cleaner but also makes it more maintainable and easier to extend with new alerts if needed.

