```java
int result = calculator.add(5, 10);
if (result > 0) {
    System.out.println("Positive");
} else if (result == 0) {
    System.out.println("Zero");
} else {
    System.out.println("Negative");
}
result = calculator.subtract(10, 5);
if (result > 0) {
    System.out.println("Positive");
} else if (result == 0) {
    System.out.println("Zero");
} else {
    System.out.println("Negative");
}
```

**Answer:**

```java
final int additionResult = calculator.add(5, 10);
printResult(additionResult);

final int subtractionResult = calculator.subtract(10, 5);
printResult(subtractionResult);

void printResult(int result) {
    if (result > 0) {
        System.out.println("Positive");
    } else if (result == 0) {
        System.out.println("Zero");
    } else {
        System.out.println("Negative");
    }
}
```

**Explanation:** The original code suffers from the Duplicate Code smell, where the logic for determining if a number is positive, zero, or negative is repeated for both the addition and subtraction results. The refactored version addresses this by extracting the repeated logic into a separate `printResult` method, promoting code reuse and improving readability.

